<% content_for :title, "HoneyOps | Privacy Policy" %>
<% content_for :meta_description, "Privacy policy for HoneyOps explaining how we collect, use, and protect personal data." %>

<div class="min-h-screen bg-slate-950 text-slate-100">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-100 sm:text-4xl">
      Privacy Policy
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-400">
      Last updated: 2025
    </p>

    <p class="mt-6 text-slate-300">
      This Privacy Policy explains how HoneyOps (&quot;we&quot;, &quot;us&quot; or &quot;our&quot;) collects,
      uses and protects personal data in connection with our website, customer portal and related services.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      1. Who we are
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      HoneyOps provides a honeypot management platform (&quot;Services&quot;) designed for organisations that want
      to deploy and monitor honeypots across their infrastructure. In most cases, we act as the
      <span class="font-medium">data controller</span> for account and user data associated with the use of our Services.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      2. Personal data we collect
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      We collect and process the following categories of personal data:
    </p>

    <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300 text-sm">
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Account and contact data</span>:
        name, surname, company name, business email address, country and billing details
        provided when creating and managing an account.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">User and authentication data</span>:
        login email address, hashed passwords (never stored in plain text), role within the account,
        and status (active, invited, disabled) managed through our authentication system.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Service usage and configuration data</span>:
        information relating to honeypots (labels, tags, policies, notification settings, maintenance windows),
        and configuration of email, webhook or syslog/SIEM destinations.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Security and event data</span>:
        logs and alerts generated when honeypots detect suspicious activity,
        including technical details about the event (IP addresses, ports, protocols and other security telemetry).
        This data is collected to enable incident detection, triage and forensic analysis.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Technical logs</span>:
        IP address, browser type, timestamps and similar information captured in server logs
        to maintain the security, availability and integrity of our Services.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Support communications</span>:
        contents of emails or requests you send us when contacting support or Sales.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      3. How we use personal data
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      We process personal data for the following purposes:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300 text-sm">
      <li>To create and manage customer accounts and user access to the HoneyOps console.</li>
      <li>To authenticate users and enforce role-based access controls.</li>
      <li>To deploy, monitor and manage honeypots and related security telemetry.</li>
      <li>To generate alerts, reports and notifications as configured by the customer.</li>
      <li>To provide customer support and respond to enquiries.</li>
      <li>To maintain and improve the security, stability and performance of our Services.</li>
      <li>To comply with legal obligations and enforce our terms of service.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      4. Legal basis for processing
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      Where the GDPR or similar laws apply, we process personal data on the following legal bases:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300 text-sm">
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Contractual necessity</span>:
        to provide and operate the Services you have requested as a customer or user.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Legitimate interests</span>:
        to ensure the security of our infrastructure, prevent abuse and improve our Services,
        provided that such interests are not overridden by your rights and freedoms.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Legal obligations</span>:
        to comply with applicable laws and regulations.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      5. Cookies and tracking
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      HoneyOps uses only strictly necessary cookies to provide secure access to the console and protect our Services.
      We do not use advertising cookies, social media tracking pixels or advanced analytics tools.
      For more information, please see our
      <%= link_to "Cookie Policy", cookies_path, class: "text-amber-400 hover:underline" %>.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      6. How we share data
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      We do not sell personal data. We may share personal data with:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300 text-sm">
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Service providers</span>:
        trusted third parties that provide infrastructure, email delivery, backup, billing
        or similar services, under written agreements and with appropriate data protection safeguards.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Authorised users</span>:
        members of your organisation who have been granted access to the HoneyOps console, based on the roles and permissions configured in your account.
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold text-slate-100">Authorities</span>:
        where required by law or necessary to protect our rights, users or the public.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      7. International transfers
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      Depending on where you are located and where our infrastructure or service providers operate,
      personal data may be processed in other countries. When we transfer personal data internationally,
      we take appropriate measures to ensure an adequate level of protection, including the use of
      contractual safeguards where required.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      8. Data retention
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      We retain personal data for as long as necessary to provide the Services, fulfil the purposes described
      in this Policy, and comply with legal, accounting or reporting obligations. Security events and logs
      may be retained for a period agreed with the customer or as reasonably necessary to support security
      investigations and compliance requirements.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">
      9. Your rights
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">
      Depending on your location and applicable law, you may have the right to:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-3 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300 text-sm">
      <li>Access the personal data we hold about you.</li>
      <li>Request correction of inaccurate or incomplete data.</li>
      <li>Request deletion of your personal data, subject to legal obligations.</li>
      <li>Object to or restrict certain types of processing.</li>
      <li>Request a copy of your data in a portable format where technically feasible.</li>
      <li>Lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority.</li>
